# Vue & TypeScript Standards

## Component Structure
- Always use `<script setup lang="ts">` for all components
- Follow multi-word component naming convention
- Group components by feature/domain
- Keep components focused and single-responsibility

## TypeScript Usage
- Enable strict mode in all TypeScript files
- Never use `any` or type casting with `as any`
- Always type props and emits properly
- Use interfaces for object shapes
- Type all ref() when type cannot be inferred

## Composition API Patterns
- Use composables for reusable logic
- Prefer ref() over reactive()
- Use computed() for derived state
- Utilize provide/inject for deep prop passing
- Use defineModel() for v-model bindings

@example-component.vue
```vue
<script setup lang="ts">
interface User {
  id: string
  name: string
  email: string
}

// Props with proper typing
const props = defineProps<{
  user: User
}>()

// Typed emits
const emit = defineEmits<{
  (e: 'update', user: User): void
  (e: 'delete', id: string): void
}>()

// Properly typed refs
const isLoading = ref<boolean>(false)
const userData = ref<User | null>(null)

// Computed properties
const userDisplay = computed(() => 
  userData.value ? `${userData.value.name} (${userData.value.email})` : 'No user'
)
</script>

<template>
  <div>
    <h1>{{ userDisplay }}</h1>
    <UButton 
      :loading="isLoading"
      @click="emit('update', props.user)"
    >
      Update User
    </UButton>
  </div>
</template>
